  "prompt": "Why is there so much moral policing in Indian schools?",
  "response": "There are several reasons for moral policing in Indian schools:\n\n1. Cultural factors\n- Strong traditional and conservative social values\n- Emphasis on discipline and conformity\n- Social expectations of maintaining \"proper\" behavior\n\n2. Educational system influences\n- Legacy of colonial-era educational structures\n- Focus on maintaining strict discipline\n- Hierarchical administration approach\n\n3. Societal pressures\n- Parents' expectations of controlling student behavior\n- Community standards and social norms\n- Fear of perceived \"Western influences\"\n\n4. Gender-related dynamics\n- Patriarchal social structures\n- Concerns about gender interactions\n- Protective attitudes towards female students\n\n5. Historical context\n- Historical emphasis on character building\n- Limited exposure to diverse perspectives\n- Resistance to social change\n\n6. Institutional control mechanisms\n- Desire to maintain institutional reputation\n- Fear of potential controversies\n- Limited understanding of youth psychology\n\n7. Lack of progressive educational policies\n- Insufficient modern pedagogical training\n- Rigid administrative frameworks\n- Limited emphasis on individual autonomy\n\nThese factors contribute to the prevalent moral policing culture in many Indian educational institutions, though perspectives are gradually evolving with younger generations and urban environments.",
